<script>

/**
 * jQuery Plugin: Sticky Tabs
 *
 * @author Aidan Lister <aidan@php.net>
 * adapted by Ruben Arslan to activate parent tabs too
 * http://www.aidanlister.com/2014/03/persisting-the-tab-state-in-bootstrap/
 */
(function($) {
  "use strict";
  $.fn.rmarkdownStickyTabs = function() {
    var context = this;
    // Show the tab corresponding with the hash in the URL, or the first tab
    var showStuffFromHash = function() {
      var hash = window.location.hash;
      var selector = hash ? 'a[href="' + hash + '"]' : 'li.active > a';
      var $selector = $(selector, context);
      if($selector.data('toggle') === "tab") {
        $selector.tab('show');
        // walk up the ancestors of this element, show any hidden tabs
        $selector.parents('.section.tabset').each(function(i, elm) {
          var link = $('a[href="#' + $(elm).attr('id') + '"]');
          if(link.data('toggle') === "tab") {
            link.tab("show");
          }
        });
      }
    };


    // Set the correct tab when the page loads
    showStuffFromHash(context);

    // Set the correct tab when a user uses their back/forward button
    $(window).on('hashchange', function() {
      showStuffFromHash(context);
    });

    // Change the URL when tabs are clicked
    $('a', context).on('click', function(e) {
      history.pushState(null, null, this.href);
      showStuffFromHash(context);
    });

    return this;
  };
}(jQuery));

window.buildTabsets = function(tocID) {

  // build a tabset from a section div with the .tabset class
  function buildTabset(tabset) {

    // check for fade and pills options
    var fade = tabset.hasClass("tabset-fade");
    var pills = tabset.hasClass("tabset-pills");
    var navClass = pills ? "nav-pills" : "nav-tabs";

    // determine the heading level of the tabset and tabs
    var match = tabset.attr('class').match(/level(\d) /);
    if (match === null)
      return;
    var tabsetLevel = Number(match[1]);
    var tabLevel = tabsetLevel + 1;

    // find all subheadings immediately below
    var tabs = tabset.find("div.section.level" + tabLevel);
    if (!tabs.length)
      return;

    // create tablist and tab-content elements
    var tabList = $('<ul class="nav ' + navClass + '" role="tablist"></ul>');
    $(tabs[0]).before(tabList);
    var tabContent = $('<div class="tab-content"></div>');
    $(tabs[0]).before(tabContent);

    // build the tabset
    var activeTab = 0;
    tabs.each(function(i) {

      // get the tab div
      var tab = $(tabs[i]);

      // get the id then sanitize it for use with bootstrap tabs
      var id = tab.attr('id');

      // see if this is marked as the active tab
      if (tab.hasClass('active'))
        activeTab = i;

      // remove any table of contents entries associated with
      // this ID (since we'll be removing the heading element)
      $("div#" + tocID + " li a[href='#" + id + "']").parent().remove();

      // sanitize the id for use with bootstrap tabs
      id = id.replace(/[.\/?&!#<>]/g, '').replace(/\s/g, '_');
      tab.attr('id', id);

      // get the heading element within it, grab it's text, then remove it
      var heading = tab.find('h' + tabLevel + ':first');
      var headingText = heading.html();
      heading.remove();

      // build and append the tab list item
      var a = $('<a role="tab" data-toggle="tab">' + headingText + '</a>');
      a.attr('href', '#' + id);
      a.attr('aria-controls', id);
      var li = $('<li role="presentation"></li>');
      li.append(a);
      tabList.append(li);

      // set it's attributes
      tab.attr('role', 'tabpanel');
      tab.addClass('tab-pane');
      tab.addClass('tabbed-pane');
      if (fade)
        tab.addClass('fade');

      // move it into the tab content div
      tab.detach().appendTo(tabContent);
    });

    // set active tab
    $(tabList.children('li')[activeTab]).addClass('active');
    var active = $(tabContent.children('div.section')[activeTab]);
    active.addClass('active');
    if (fade)
      active.addClass('in');

    if (tabset.hasClass("tabset-sticky"))
      tabset.rmarkdownStickyTabs();
  }

  // convert section divs with the .tabset class to tabsets
  var tabsets = $("div.section.tabset");
  tabsets.each(function(i) {
    buildTabset($(tabsets[i]));
  });
};

</script>

<div id="regression-models-fitting-them-and-evaluating-their-performance" class="section level2 tabset">
<h2>Regression models: fitting them and evaluating their performance</h2>
<div id="supervised-vs.-unsupersived-learning" class="section level3">
<h3>Supervised vs. Unsupersived Learning</h3>
<ul>
<li>Predictive Modeling = Supervised Learning</li>
<li>Supervised Learning = Machine Learning if you have a target variable</li>
<li>Two types of predictive modeling
<ul>
<li>Classification (Qualitative)</li>
<li>Regression (Quantitative)</li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
</div>
<div id="evaluating-model-perfomance" class="section level3">
<h3>Evaluating Model Perfomance</h3>
<ul>
<li>Use <em>metrics</em> to evaluate a model. It is:
<ul>
<li>Quantifiable</li>
<li>Objective</li>
</ul></li>
<li><em>Root Mean Squared Error</em> (RMSE) for regression</li>
<li>Common to calculate in-sample RMSE. Problems:
<ul>
<li>Too optimistic since model is trained on the same data that you are calculating RMSE on</li>
<li>Leads to overfitting</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Better to calculate out-of-sample error
<ul>
<li>Simulates real world usage</li>
<li>Helps avoid overfitting</li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<pre class="r"><code>## Computing the RMSE on the diamonds data set
library(caret)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## Loading required package: lattice</code></pre>
<pre><code>## Loading required package: ggplot2</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>library(ggplot2)
library(tidyverse)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## -- Attaching packages ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------- tidyverse 1.3.0 --</code></pre>
<pre><code>## v tibble  3.0.1     v dplyr   1.0.0
## v tidyr   1.1.0     v stringr 1.4.0
## v readr   1.3.1     v forcats 0.5.0
## v purrr   0.3.4</code></pre>
<pre><code>## -- Conflicts ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- tidyverse_conflicts() --
## x dplyr::filter() masks stats::filter()
## x dplyr::lag()    masks stats::lag()
## x purrr::lift()   masks caret::lift()</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>library(dplyr)
data(&quot;diamonds&quot;)

# Fit lm model: model
model &lt;- lm(price ~ ., diamonds) 

# Predict on full data: p
p &lt;- predict(model, type=&quot;response&quot;)

# Compute errors: error
error &lt;- p - diamonds$price

# Calculate RMSE
sqrt(mean((error)^2))</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 1129.843</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="out-of-sample-error-measures" class="section level3">
<h3>Out-of-sample error measures</h3>
<ul>
<li>Objective: Want models that don’t overfit and generalize well (<span class="math inline">\(\neq\)</span> explanatory modeling)</li>
<li>Do the models perform well on new data?</li>
<li>Test models on new data, or test set
<ul>
<li>Key insight of machine learning</li>
<li>In-sample validation almost guarantees overfitting ==&gt; We try to simulate this by applying a train/test split</li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<pre class="r"><code>## First we randomly shuffle the data so that potential clusters or imbalances are disaggregated
# Set seed so this can be reproduced
set.seed(42)

# Shuffle row indices: rows
rows &lt;- sample(nrow(diamonds)) 

# Randomly order data
shuffled_diamonds &lt;- diamonds[rows,]

# Determine row to split on: split (at 80%)
split &lt;- round(nrow(shuffled_diamonds)*0.8)

# Create train
train &lt;- shuffled_diamonds[1:split,]

# Create test
test &lt;- shuffled_diamonds[(split+1):nrow(shuffled_diamonds),]

# Fit lm model on train: model
model &lt;- lm(price ~ ., train) 

# Predict on test: p
p &lt;- predict(model, test)

# Compute errors: error
error &lt;- p - test$price

# Calculate RMSE
sqrt(mean(error^2))</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 1137.466</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code># The model is worse than we initially thought!</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="cross-validation" class="section level3">
<h3>Cross-validation</h3>
<ul>
<li>One simple split is fragile as a process, as one single outlier could cause problems</li>
<li>Better approach is to have several test done, with: - Equally sized test sets
<ul>
<li>Over k-fold amount of sets (e.g. ten)</li>
<li>And averaging out the out-of-sample error measures</li>
</ul></li>
<li>The <code>train</code> function (<code>caret</code>) can do that for us!</li>
</ul>
<pre class="r"><code># Fit lm model using 10-fold CV: model
model &lt;- train(
  price ~ ., 
  diamonds,
  method = &quot;lm&quot;,
  trControl = trainControl(
    method = &quot;cv&quot;, 
    number = 10,
    verboseIter = TRUE
  )
)</code></pre>

<div id="classification-models-fitting-them-and-evaluating-their-performance" class="section level2 tabset">
<h2>Classification models: fitting them and evaluating their performance</h2>
<div id="logistic-regression-on-sonar" class="section level3">
<h3>Logistic Regression on <code>sonar</code></h3>
<ul>
<li>Classification Models:
<ul>
<li>Categorical (i.e. qualitative) target variable</li>
<li>Example: will a loan default?</li>
<li>Still a form of supervised learning</li>
<li>Use a train/test split to evaluate performance</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Splitting the data:
<ul>
<li>The task will include a logistic regression on the <code>sonar</code> data set, to predict rocks/mines.</li>
<li>Here we will use a 60/40 split for Cross-Validation</li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<pre class="r"><code>library(mlbench)
data(&quot;Sonar&quot;)

set.seed(313)
# Get the number of observations
n_obs &lt;- nrow(Sonar)

# Shuffle row indices: permuted_rows
permuted_rows &lt;- sample(n_obs)

# Randomly order data: Sonar
Sonar_shuffled &lt;- Sonar[permuted_rows,]

# Identify row to split on: split
split &lt;- round(n_obs * 0.6)

# Create train
train &lt;- Sonar_shuffled[1:split,]

# Create test
test &lt;- Sonar_shuffled[(split+1):n_obs,]

# Did the split work? Yes!
list(nrow(test)/nrow(Sonar), nrow(train)/nrow(Sonar))</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [[1]]
## [1] 0.3990385
## 
## [[2]]
## [1] 0.6009615</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code># Fit glm model: model
model &lt;- glm(Class ~ ., binomial(link = &quot;logit&quot;), data=train)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## Warning: glm.fit: algorithm did not converge</code></pre>
<pre><code>## Warning: glm.fit: fitted probabilities numerically 0 or 1 occurred</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>## Don&#39;t worry of the fit not converging
# Predict on test: p
p &lt;- predict.glm(model, newdata=test, type=&quot;response&quot;)</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="confusion-matrix" class="section level3">
<h3>Confusion matrix</h3>
<p>We use this to evaluate the performance of a classification model. We display predicted classes vs. actual outcomes Confusion matrix: As whether an outcome got “confused” for anouther. Typically it’ll look like this:</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr class="header">
<th></th>
<th align="center"></th>
<th align="center"><strong>Reference</strong></th>
<th></th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr class="odd">
<td></td>
<td align="center"></td>
<td align="center"><strong>Yes</strong></td>
<td><strong>No</strong></td>
</tr>
<tr class="even">
<td><strong>Prediction</strong></td>
<td align="center"><strong>Yes</strong></td>
<td align="center"><em>True Positives</em></td>
<td><em>False Positives</em></td>
</tr>
<tr class="odd">
<td></td>
<td align="center"><strong>No</strong></td>
<td align="center"><em>False Negatives</em></td>
<td><em>True Negatives</em></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>As we usually predict probabilities in regards to categorical data and not linear predictions (don’t get it confused with the linear combination of the regression model), the objective should be to find a measure to code the probabilities into a binary outcome. Here we can turn the probabilities into classes by choosing a threshold at which a greater value is a positive and a lower value is a negative outcome.</p>
<pre class="r"><code># If p exceeds threshold of 0.5 (50%), M else R: m_or_r
m_or_r &lt;- ifelse(p &gt; 0.5, &quot;M&quot;, &quot;R&quot;)

# Convert to factor: p_class
p_class &lt;- as.factor(m_or_r)

# Create confusion matrix
confusionMatrix(p_class, test$Class)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## Confusion Matrix and Statistics
## 
##           Reference
## Prediction  M  R
##          M 19 27
##          R 29  8
##                                          
##                Accuracy : 0.3253         
##                  95% CI : (0.2265, 0.437)
##     No Information Rate : 0.5783         
##     P-Value [Acc &gt; NIR] : 1.0000         
##                                          
##                   Kappa : -0.3727        
##                                          
##  Mcnemar&#39;s Test P-Value : 0.8937         
##                                          
##             Sensitivity : 0.3958         
##             Specificity : 0.2286         
##          Pos Pred Value : 0.4130         
##          Neg Pred Value : 0.2162         
##              Prevalence : 0.5783         
##          Detection Rate : 0.2289         
##    Detection Prevalence : 0.5542         
##       Balanced Accuracy : 0.3122         
##                                          
##        &#39;Positive&#39; Class : M              
## </code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>### What do we see:
# Accuracy: How correct were we (percentage)
# No Information Rate: How correct would we have been, if we predicted everything as the most dominant class (here Mines)
# Sensitivity: True Positives Rate
# Specificity: True Negatives Rate</code></pre>
<ul>
<li>Not limited to to 50% threshold
<ul>
<li>10% would catch more mines with less certainty (higher false positive; higher true positives)</li>
<li>90% would catch fewer mines with more certainty (lower false positive: lower true positives)</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Choosing a threshold means a balance between true positive and false positive rates</li>
<li>Choosing threshold is dependent on cost-benefit-analysis</li>
</ul>
<pre class="r"><code># If p exceeds threshold of 0.9 (90%), M else R: m_or_r
m_or_r &lt;- ifelse(p&gt;0.9, &quot;M&quot;, &quot;R&quot;)

# Convert to factor: p_class
p_class &lt;- as.factor(m_or_r)

# Create confusion matrix
confusionMatrix(p_class, test$Class)</code></pre>

<div id="intoducing-the-roc-curve" class="section level3">
<h3>Intoducing the ROC curve</h3>
<p>The challenge with evaluating the performance of a classification model via confusion matrices is to find the right amount of thresholds (many) without arbitrarily running a sequence classifications and ending up overlooking important thresholds.</p>
<ul>
<li>The challenge:
<ul>
<li>Many possible classification thresholds</li>
<li>Requires manual work to choose</li>
<li>Easy to overlook a particular threshold</li>
<li>We need a more systematic approach</li>
</ul></li>
<li>ROC Curves:
<ul>
<li>Plot true/false positive rate at every possible threshold</li>
<li>Visualize tradeoffs between two extremes (100% true positives vs 0% false positive)</li>
<li>Result is an ROC curve</li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<pre class="r"><code>library(caTools)
colAUC(p, test$Class, plotROC = TRUE)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<pre><code>##              [,1]
## M vs. R 0.7366071</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code># Every point shows us a threshold
# Y-Axis: True positives
# X-Axis: False positives</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="area-under-the-curve-auc" class="section level3">
<h3>Area under the curve (AUC)</h3>
<ul>
<li>We can say following about the curve itself:
<ul>
<li>Random predictions would follow a (close to) linear line</li>
<li>Perfect predictions would create something like a box, where a single point would predict all positives while detecting no false positives. Results in a lot of space under the curve</li>
<li>Perfectly incorrect predictions (rarely happen) would create a box with the opposite factum - no true positives all false positives. Results in no space under the curve.</li>
</ul></li>
<li>The area under the curve (AUC) would basically tell us how good model perform. Numerically speaking this would mean:
<ul>
<li>All the space under the curve is available = perfect prediction = Values as 1</li>
<li>Half of the space under the curve is available = random prediction = Values as 0.5</li>
<li>No space under the curve is available = perfectly false prediction = Values as 0</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Defining AUC as a metric:
<ul>
<li>Single-number summary of model accuracy</li>
<li>Summarizes performance accross all thresholds</li>
<li>Can be used to rank different models within the same dataset</li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<pre class="r"><code># Create trainControl object: myControl
# This allows use to feed this to the train function
# We use 10 iterations here for the cross-validation
# we use a twoClassSummary wo the binary outcome to be produced (instead of defaultSummary)
# When choosing twoClassSummary we need to set classProbs on True
# We are trying to get evualuation metrics over a 10-fold cross validation and averaging them out.
myControl &lt;- trainControl(
  method = &quot;cv&quot;,
  number = 10,
  summaryFunction = twoClassSummary,
  classProbs = TRUE, # IMPORTANT!
  verboseIter = TRUE
)

# Train glm with custom trainControl: model
model &lt;- train(Class ~., Sonar, method=&quot;glm&quot;, trControl=myControl)</code></pre>

<div id="tuning-model-parameters-to-improve-performance" class="section level2 tabset">
<h2>Tuning model parameters to improve performance</h2>
<div id="random-forests-and-wine" class="section level3">
<h3>Random forests and wine</h3>
<ul>
<li>Random forest
<ul>
<li>Popular type of machien learning model</li>
<li>Good for beginners</li>
<li>Robust to overfitting</li>
<li>Yield very accurate, non-linear models</li>
<li>Default values often OK, but occasionally need adjustment</li>
<li>These adjustments on hyperparameters need to be manually justified, unlike other methods like the slope in a linear model</li>
</ul></li>
<li>What does it do?
<ul>
<li>Start with a simple desicion tree</li>
<li>Decision trees are fast, but not very accurate</li>
<li>Random forests improve accuracy by fitting many trees</li>
<li>Fit each one to a bootstrap sample of your data</li>
<li>Called <em>bootstrap aggregation</em> or <em>bagging</em></li>
<li>Randomly sample columns at each split. Meaning what information the decision split will be based on (randomly)</li>
<li>Each individual tree in the random forest spits out a class prediction and the class with the most votes becomes our model’s prediction</li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<pre class="r"><code>white.url &lt;- &quot;https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/wine-quality/winequality-white.csv&quot;
white.raw &lt;- read.csv(white.url, header = TRUE, sep = &quot;;&quot;)
wine &lt;- white.raw
glimpse(wine)</code></pre>

<div id="explore-a-wider-model-space" class="section level3">
<h3>Explore a wider model space</h3>
<ul>
<li>Random forests require tuning
<ul>
<li>Hyperparameters control how the model is fit</li>
<li>Selected “by hand” before the model is fit</li>
<li>Most important is <code>mtry</code>
<ul>
<li>Number of randomly selected variables used at each split</li>
<li>“Randomly sample columns at each split” as I mentioned above</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Lower <code>mtry</code> value = more random (more to choose)</li>
<li>Higher <code>mtry</code> value = less random (less to choose)</li>
<li>Hard to know the best value in advance</li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<p>The <code>train</code> function automatically models for different values of <code>mtry</code> for us to inspect and choose. It automatically fits a final model with the optimal parameters (see the report of the command or <code>model[[&quot;finalModel&quot;]]</code>). The results below show us: <code>extraTreets</code> as a splitting rule, implementing <a href="https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10994-006-6226-1">Extra randomized trees</a>, performs worse than <code>variance</code>. A value of 6 for <code>mtry</code> (randomly selected predictors) seems to be the best option to minimize errors (RMSE).</p>
<pre class="r"><code># Fit random forest: model
model &lt;- train(
  quality ~.,
  tuneLength = 3,
  data = wine, 
  method = &quot;ranger&quot;,
  trControl = trainControl(
    method = &quot;cv&quot;, 
    number = 5, 
    verboseIter = TRUE
  )
)</code></pre>

<div id="custom-tuning-grids" class="section level3">
<h3>Custom tuning grids</h3>
<p>We are not bound to the default settings of the tuning grids Pros and cons of custom tuning:</p>
<ul>
<li>Pass custom tuning grids to <code>tuneGrid</code> argument</li>
<li>Advantages
<ul>
<li>Most flexible method for fitting <code>caret</code> models</li>
<li>Complete control over how the model is fit</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Disadvantages
<ul>
<li>Requires some knowledge of the model</li>
<li>Can dramatically increase run time</li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<p>In the results below we try 2,3 and 7 as values of <code>mtry</code> of the splitting rule being variance based. Here optimal value for <code>mtry</code> seems to be 3. It equals to a RMSE of 0.6098126, which is slightly worse than the 0.6005850 from <code>variance</code> and 6 random predictors.</p>
<pre class="r"><code># Define the tuning grid: tuneGrid
tuneGrid &lt;- data.frame(
  .mtry = c(2,3,7),        ## Custom rangeo of mtry to explore
  .splitrule = &quot;variance&quot;, ## One split rule
  .min.node.size = 5       ## Minimum number of observations in a terminal node 
)

# Fit random forest: model
model &lt;- train(
  quality ~.,
  tuneGrid = tuneGrid,     ## Here we insert our custom tuneGrid
  data = wine, 
  method = &quot;ranger&quot;,
  trControl = trainControl(
    method = &quot;cv&quot;, 
    number = 5, 
    verboseIter = TRUE
  )
)</code></pre>

<div id="glmnet" class="section level3">
<h3>glmnet</h3>
<p>Introducing glmnet:</p>
<ul>
<li>Extension of glm models with built-in variable selection</li>
<li>Helps deal with collinearity and small samples sizes</li>
<li>Two primary forms
<ul>
<li>Lasso regression: penalizes number of non-zero coefficients (resulting in a few non-zero coef.)</li>
<li>Ridge regression: penalizes absolute magnitude of coefficients (small absolute magnitude coefficients)</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Attempts to find a parsimonious (i.e. simple) model</li>
<li>Pairs well with random forest models</li>
</ul>
<p>Tuning glmnet models:</p>
<ul>
<li>Combination of lasso and ridge regression</li>
<li>Can fit a mix of the models, thas is a model with a small penalty on both the:
<ul>
<li>number of non-zero coefficients</li>
<li>and their absolute magnitude</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Therefore there are many parameters to tune:
<ul>
<li><code>alpha [0,1]</code>: pure ridge (0) to pure lasso (1)</li>
<li><code>lambda (0,infinity)</code>: size of the penalty. The higher the value to smaller the value. Hence, if we tune the number large enough there would be an intercept only model</li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<p>The results below show an optimal model at alpha = 1 (lasso) and lambda (penality) of 0.029900470</p>
<pre class="r"><code># Create custom trainControl: myControl
myControl &lt;- trainControl(
  method = &quot;cv&quot;, 
  number = 10,
  summaryFunction = twoClassSummary,
  classProbs = TRUE, # IMPORTANT!
  verboseIter = TRUE
)

# Fit glmnet model with the overfit data: model
overfit &lt;- read.csv(&quot;train.csv&quot;)
overfit &lt;- overfit[,-1]
names(overfit)[names(overfit)==&quot;target&quot;] &lt;- &quot;y&quot;
overfit$y[overfit$y == &quot;0&quot;] &lt;- &quot;class1&quot;
overfit$y[overfit$y == &quot;1&quot;] &lt;- &quot;class2&quot;
names(overfit)[names(overfit)==&quot;X0&quot;] &lt;- &quot;X300&quot;
overfit$y &lt;- as.factor(overfit$y)

model &lt;- train(
  y~., 
  overfit,
  method = &quot;glmnet&quot;,
  trControl = myControl
)</code></pre>

<div id="glmnet-with-custom-tuning-grid" class="section level3">
<h3>glmnet with custom tuning grid</h3>
<ul>
<li>random forest had only one tuning param.: mtry</li>
<li>glmnet has two: alpha and lambda</li>
<li>for single alpha, all values of lambda fit simultaneously (fits several alpha in one alpha model)</li>
<li>Many models for the “price” of one</li>
</ul>
<p>“The final values used for the model were alpha = 1 and lambda = 0.05272632.”</p>
<pre class="r"><code># Train glmnet with custom trainControl and tuning: model
model &lt;- train(
  y~., 
  overfit,
  tuneGrid = expand.grid(
    alpha=0:1, # 2 values of alpha
    lambda=seq(0.0001, 1, length=20) # 20 values of lambda
  ),
  method = &quot;glmnet&quot;,
  trControl = myControl # 10-fold CV from before
)</code></pre>

<div id="preprocessing-your-data" class="section level2 tabset">
<h2>Preprocessing your data</h2>
<div id="median-imputation" class="section level3">
<h3>Median imputation</h3>
<p>Dealing with missing values:</p>
<ul>
<li>Real-world data has missing values</li>
<li>Most models require numbers, can’t handle missing data</li>
<li>Common approach: remove rows with missing data
<ul>
<li>Can lead to biases in data</li>
<li>Generate over-confident models</li>
</ul></li>
<li>The authors of the caret package favor a median imputation
<ul>
<li>Replace missing values with medians</li>
<li>Works well if data is missing at random (MAR)</li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<pre class="r"><code># Getting the data
cancer.url &lt;- &quot;http://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/breast-cancer-wisconsin/breast-cancer-wisconsin.data&quot;
cancer.raw &lt;- read.csv(cancer.url, header = TRUE)
BreastCancer &lt;- cancer.raw[,-1]

# Correcting the variable names
columns &lt;- c(&quot;Cl.thickness&quot;, &quot;Cell.size&quot;, &quot;Cell.shape&quot;, &quot;Marg.adhesion&quot;, &quot;Epith.c.size&quot;, &quot;Bare.nuclei&quot;, &quot;Bl.cromatin&quot;, &quot;Normal.nucleoli&quot;, &quot;Mitoses&quot;, &quot;Class&quot;)
names(BreastCancer) &lt;- columns
glimpse(BreastCancer)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## Rows: 698
## Columns: 10
## $ Cl.thickness    &lt;int&gt; 5, 3, 6, 4, 8, 1, 2, 2, 4, 1, 2, 5, 1, 8, 7, 4, 4, ...
## $ Cell.size       &lt;int&gt; 4, 1, 8, 1, 10, 1, 1, 1, 2, 1, 1, 3, 1, 7, 4, 1, 1,...
## $ Cell.shape      &lt;int&gt; 4, 1, 8, 1, 10, 1, 2, 1, 1, 1, 1, 3, 1, 5, 6, 1, 1,...
## $ Marg.adhesion   &lt;int&gt; 5, 1, 1, 3, 8, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 3, 1, 10, 4, 1, 1,...
## $ Epith.c.size    &lt;int&gt; 7, 2, 3, 2, 7, 2, 2, 2, 2, 1, 2, 2, 2, 7, 6, 2, 2, ...
## $ Bare.nuclei     &lt;chr&gt; &quot;10&quot;, &quot;2&quot;, &quot;4&quot;, &quot;1&quot;, &quot;10&quot;, &quot;10&quot;, &quot;1&quot;, &quot;1&quot;, &quot;1&quot;, &quot;1&quot;...
## $ Bl.cromatin     &lt;int&gt; 3, 3, 3, 3, 9, 3, 3, 1, 2, 3, 2, 4, 3, 5, 4, 2, 3, ...
## $ Normal.nucleoli &lt;int&gt; 2, 1, 7, 1, 7, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 4, 1, 5, 3, 1, 1, ...
## $ Mitoses         &lt;int&gt; 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 5, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 4, 1, 1, 1, ...
## $ Class           &lt;int&gt; 2, 2, 2, 2, 4, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 4, 2, 4, 4, 2, 2, ...</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code># Splitting the data in x and y
# Creating two data-sets
breast_cancer_x &lt;- BreastCancer[,c(1:9)]
breast_cancer_y &lt;- BreastCancer[,10]

names_x &lt;- names(breast_cancer_x)
# Creating Missings at Random (MAR)

set.seed(42)
for(val in names_x){
    breast_cancer_x[sample(1:nrow(breast_cancer_x), 100), val] &lt;- NA
}

#Recode breast_cancer_y with ifelse
breast_cancer_y &lt;- ifelse(breast_cancer_y==2, &quot;benign&quot;, &quot;malignant&quot;)

# Apply median imputation: median_model
median_model &lt;- train(
  x = breast_cancer_x, 
  y = breast_cancer_y,
  method = &quot;glm&quot;,
  trControl = myControl,
  preProcess = &quot;medianImpute&quot;
)</code></pre>

<div id="my-advise-against-meanmedian-imputation" class="section level3">
<h3>My advise against mean/median imputation!</h3>
<p>To this day, a lot of teachers and manuals advise mean and median imputations for replacing missing values in their data sets. I find this highly problematic because these methods skew your results.</p>
<p>The problem with mean imputations:</p>
<ul>
<li>Let’s have a look at the formula for the standard deviation: <span class="math inline">\(\sqrt{\frac{1}{N-1}\sum \limits_{i=1}^N (x_i-\bar{x})}\)</span>, with <span class="math inline">\(x_i\)</span> being the observed value and <span class="math inline">\(\bar{x}\)</span> the mean of all observations.</li>
<li>If we would impute a missing value with the mean, <span class="math inline">\(x_i\)</span> would equal to <span class="math inline">\(\bar{x}\)</span>.</li>
<li>This would lead the substrate of <span class="math inline">\(x_i-\bar{x}\)</span> to be 0! Ultimately decreasing the variance in your data</li>
<li>For those interested in Confidence Intervals and p-Values: Since the formula of the standard deviation is used to calculate these metrics, we would underestimate the size both of these metrics. This would lead you to be overconfident with your results!</li>
</ul>
<p>Similar problems could occur with median imputations. Often the mean and median of a distribution are close to each other. They are so the more symmetrically distributed your data is!</p>
<p>Even when in regards to predictive modeling, incorrect results can be produced if data is missing not at random!</p>
</div>
<div id="knn-imputation" class="section level3">
<h3>KNN imputation</h3>
<p>As an alternative to median imputation:</p>
<ul>
<li>k-nearest neighbors (KNN) imputation</li>
<li>Imputes based on “similar” non-missing rows</li>
<li>The <code>train</code> function implements KNN imputations</li>
</ul>
<p>When missing values are not at random, KNN imputation is better and yields more accurate (but slower) results than median imputation.</p>
<p>As you can see in the results below, the KNN-imputation performs slightly better than the median one!</p>
<pre class="r"><code># Apply KNN imputation: knn_model
set.seed(42)
knn_model &lt;- train(
  x = breast_cancer_x, 
  y = breast_cancer_y,
  method = &quot;glm&quot;,
  trControl = myControl,
  preProcess = &quot;knnImpute&quot;
)</code></pre>

<div id="multiple-preprocessing-methods" class="section level3">
<h3>Multiple preprocessing methods</h3>
<p>The wide world of preProcess:</p>
<ul>
<li>You can do a lot more than median or knn imputation!</li>
<li>Can chain together multiplte preprocessing steps</li>
<li>Common “recipe” for linear models (order matters!)
<ul>
<li>Median imputation =&gt; center =&gt; scale =&gt; fit glm</li>
<li>Principle Component Analysis (PCA) always happens after centering and scaling the data</li>
</ul></li>
<li>See <code>?preProcess</code> for more details</li>
</ul>
<p>Preprocessing cheat sheet:</p>
<ul>
<li>Start with median imputation</li>
<li>Try KNN imputation if data missing not at random</li>
<li>For linear models (lm, glm, glmnet, etc.)…
<ul>
<li>Center and scale</li>
<li>Try PCA and spatial sign (<code>spatialSign</code>, for data with many outliers or high dimensional data)</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Tree-based models don’t need much preprocessing. Often you get away with just median imputation.</li>
</ul>
<pre class="r"><code>model &lt;- train(
  x = breast_cancer_x, 
  y = breast_cancer_y,
  method = &quot;glm&quot;,
  trControl = myControl,
  preProcess = c(&quot;medianImpute&quot;,&quot;center&quot;,&quot;scale&quot;)
)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## Warning in train.default(x = breast_cancer_x, y = breast_cancer_y, method =
## &quot;glm&quot;, : The metric &quot;Accuracy&quot; was not in the result set. ROC will be used
## instead.</code></pre>
<pre><code>## + Fold01: parameter=none 
## - Fold01: parameter=none 
## + Fold02: parameter=none 
## - Fold02: parameter=none 
## + Fold03: parameter=none 
## - Fold03: parameter=none

<div id="handling-low-information-predicators" class="section level3">
<h3>Handling low-information predicators</h3>
<p>No (or low) variance variables:</p>
<ul>
<li>Some variables don’t contain much information
<ul>
<li>Constant (i.e. no variance)</li>
<li>Nearly constant (i.e. low variance)</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Easy for one fold of CV to end up with constant column
<ul>
<li>Can cause problems for your models</li>
<li>Tend to have no impact on your model, as they have contibute variance/information to it.</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Common practice is: Remove extremely low variance variables
<ul>
<li>Runs faster</li>
<li>Does not have much impact on your model accuracy</li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<p>The <code>caret</code> way to deal with this:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>zv</code> removes constant columns</li>
<li><code>nzv</code> removes nearly constant columns</li>
<li>These variables can be removed a-priori or within the train process, as method in <code>preProcess</code></li>
</ul>
<pre class="r"><code>data(BloodBrain)

bloodbrain_x &lt;- bbbDescr
bloodbrain_y &lt;- logBBB

# Identify near zero variance predictors: remove_cols
remove_cols &lt;- nearZeroVar(bloodbrain_x, names = TRUE, freqCut = 2, uniqueCut = 20)

# Get all column names from bloodbrain_x: all_cols
all_cols &lt;- names(bloodbrain_x)

# Remove from data: bloodbrain_x_small
bloodbrain_x_small &lt;- bloodbrain_x[ , setdiff(all_cols, remove_cols)]

# Fit model on reduced data: model
model &lt;- train(
  x = bloodbrain_x_small, 
  y = bloodbrain_y, 
  method = &quot;glm&quot;
)</code></pre>

<div id="principle-components-analysis-pca" class="section level3">
<h3>Principle components analysis (PCA)</h3>
<ul>
<li>We know PCA as a form of analysis that allows to find structure in our data and cluster certain informations</li>
<li>As a preprocessing function, we can use PCA to combine low-variance and correlated variables</li>
<li>Into a single set of high-variance, perpendicular predictors</li>
<li>It’s better to find a systematic way to use that information rather tahan throwing it away</li>
<li>Prevents collinearity (i.e. correlation among predictors)</li>
</ul>
<p>PCA searches for high-variance, linear combination of the input-data that are perpendicular to each other:</p>
<ul>
<li>The first component has highest variance</li>
<li>Second component has second variance</li>
<li>And so on …</li>
</ul>
<p>Look at the figure below. We have two correlated variables, x and y. When plotted together we can see the relationship. PCA transforms this data with respect to that correlation and finds a new variable - the long diagonal arrow pointing up and to the right (first component). That reflects the shared correlation between x and y. The second component has to be orthogonal to the first one - shown in the second arrow, going up and to the left. The first PCA component reflects the similarity between x and y, while the second one emphasized their difference. <img src="data:image/png;base64," style="width:50.0%" alt="PCA|250x250" /></p>
<pre class="r"><code>data(BloodBrain)

bloodbrain_x &lt;- bbbDescr
bloodbrain_y &lt;- logBBB

# Fit glm model using PCA: model
model &lt;- train(
  x = bloodbrain_x, 
  y = bloodbrain_y,
  method = &quot;glm&quot;, 
  preProcess = c(&quot;zv&quot;,&quot;pca&quot;)
)

# Print model to console
model</code></pre>

<div id="selecting-models-a-case-study-in-churn-prediction" class="section level2 tabset">
<h2>Selecting models: a case study in churn prediction</h2>
<div id="reusing-a-traincontrol" class="section level3">
<h3>Reusing a <code>trainControl</code></h3>
<p>A real-world example: + The data: customer churn at a telecom company + Fit different models and choose the best + Models must use the same training/test splits + We can do that by creating a shared <code>trainControl</code> object. This specifies which rows we use for model-building.</p>
<p>Note: When doing CV, caret tries to keep the ratio of positive to negative results in the fold-data as in the data overall (here approx. 15/85).</p>
<pre class="r"><code># Get the data from Github
library(BDgraph)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## Registered S3 methods overwritten by &#39;BDgraph&#39;:
##   method    from
##   plot.sim  lava
##   print.sim lava</code></pre>
<pre><code>## 
## Attaching package: &#39;BDgraph&#39;</code></pre>
<pre><code>## The following object is masked from &#39;package:MASS&#39;:
## 
##     select</code></pre>
<pre><code>## The following object is masked from &#39;package:dplyr&#39;:
## 
##     select</code></pre>
<pre><code>## The following object is masked from &#39;package:caret&#39;:
## 
##     precision</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>data(&quot;churn&quot;)

#Churn y and x
churn_y &lt;- churn$Churn
churn_x &lt;- churn[,-20]
  
# Create custom indices: myFolds (for a 5-fold CV)
myFolds &lt;- createFolds(churn_y, k = 5)

# Create reusable trainControl object: myControl
myControl &lt;- trainControl(
  summaryFunction = twoClassSummary,
  classProbs = TRUE, # IMPORTANT!
  verboseIter = TRUE,
  savePredictions = TRUE,
  index = myFolds
)</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="reintroducing-glmnet" class="section level3">
<h3>Reintroducing glmnet</h3>
<p>glmnet review:</p>
<ul>
<li>Linear model with built-in variable selection</li>
<li>Great baselne model</li>
<li>Advantages:
<ul>
<li>Fits quickly</li>
<li>Ignores noisy variables</li>
<li>Provides interpretable coefficients (just like in lm or glm)</li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<pre class="r"><code># Fit glmnet model: model_glmnet
train &lt;- data.frame(churn_x, churn_y) 

model_glmnet &lt;- train(churn_y ~ ., data = train,
  metric = &quot;ROC&quot;,
  method = &quot;glmnet&quot;,
  trControl = myControl
)</code></pre>

<div id="reintroducing-random-forest" class="section level3">
<h3>Reintroducing random forest</h3>
<p>Random forest review;</p>
<ul>
<li>Slower to fit than glmnet</li>
<li>Less interpretable</li>
<li>Often (but not always) more accurate than glmnet</li>
<li>Easier to tune (only one parameter <code>mtry</code>)</li>
<li>Require little preprocessing. Random forest models are more robust to zero/near-zero variance variables, outliers, collinearity, and missings not at random etc.</li>
<li>Capture threshold effects and variable interactions</li>
</ul>
<pre class="r"><code># Fit random forest: model_rf
model_rf &lt;- train(churn_y ~ ., data = train,
  metric = &quot;ROC&quot;,
  method = &quot;ranger&quot;,
  trControl = myControl
)</code></pre>

<div id="comparing-models" class="section level3">
<h3>Comparing models</h3>
<p>After fitting two or more models, we can compare them to see wich one fits new data the best:</p>
<ul>
<li>Make sure they were fit on the same data!</li>
<li>Selection criteria:
<ul>
<li>Highest average AUC</li>
<li>Lowest standard deviation in AUC</li>
</ul></li>
<li>The <code>resamples()</code> function, as used before, helps us doing this</li>
</ul>
<pre class="r"><code># Create model_list
model_list &lt;- list(glmnet = model_glmnet, rf = model_rf)

# Pass model_list to resamples(): resamples
resamples &lt;- resamples(model_list)

# Summarize the results
summary(resamples)</code></pre>
